ACK b39fec7379d069d138c0e60cb41c86c7e84686fb

Since we're not logging consistently (e.g. [this path is not logged](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/28569/files#diff-97c3a52bc5fad452d82670a7fd291800bae20c7bc35bb82686c2c0a4ea7b5b98R5718-R5733)), I think I'd be in favour of just removing both log lines until we implement it properly, though:

<details>
<summary>git diff</summary>

```diff
diff --git a/src/validation.cpp b/src/validation.cpp
index d4b30e397c..ab0eb1a6aa 100644
--- a/src/validation.cpp
+++ b/src/validation.cpp
@@ -5701,17 +5701,11 @@ void ChainstateManager::MaybeRebalanceCaches()
     assert(ibd_usable || snapshot_usable);
 
     if (ibd_usable && !snapshot_usable) {
-        if (m_snapshot_chainstate) {
-            // In normal mode, without a snapshot chainstate present, this log
-            // message is confusing.
-            LogPrintf("[snapshot] allocating all cache to the IBD chainstate\n");
-        }
         // Allocate everything to the IBD chainstate.
         m_ibd_chainstate->ResizeCoinsCaches(m_total_coinstip_cache, m_total_coinsdb_cache);
     }
     else if (snapshot_usable && !ibd_usable) {
         // If background validation has completed and snapshot is our active chain...
-        LogPrintf("[snapshot] allocating all cache to the snapshot chainstate\n");
         // Allocate everything to the snapshot chainstate.
         m_snapshot_chainstate->ResizeCoinsCaches(m_total_coinstip_cache, m_total_coinsdb_cache);
     }

```
</details>

Regardless, this is not worth holding things up so I'd be comfortable with either approach (or making both these log statements DEBUG).

I have removed the line since it sounds like the preferred approach from @stickies-v and @fanquake and otherwise people feel indifferent.

> removing both log lines

@stickies-v I have kept the second one in for now since this one isn't hurting IMO. In the context of the snapshot being present it may be valuable to log this though I agree this can be made more consistent again in a follow-up.
